message:
Fantastic! Let's demystify printf .

printf  is a super useful function in C that allows your program to print text, 
numbers, and other information to the console (that's the black screen where 
your program runs). Think of it as your program's way of speaking to the 
user.

Here's a very simple example:

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

printf("Hello, world!");
   return 0;
}

When you run this tiny program, what do you think will appear on your 
screen? Take a guess!

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int n;
scanf("%d", &n);
return n+ 1

float n1;
float n2;
float n3;

Awesome! You've nailed it! Using scanf("%f %f %f %f", &n1, &n2, &n3,

&n4);  is a perfectly valid and efficient way to read all four float values at 
once. The user can type them all on one line separated by spaces, or press 
Enter after each one.

So far, you have declared your variables and you're successfully reading 
input from the user. That's a huge step!

C

#include <stdio.h> // We'll need this for printf and scanf

int main() {

float n1;
   float n2;

float n3;
   float n4;

printf("Enter four numbers, separated by spaces: ");
   scanf("%f %f %f %f", &n1, &n2, &n3, &n4);

// What comes next?
   return 0;
}

Now that you have n1 , n2 , n3 , and n4  holding the numbers, what's the 
next logical step to calculate the arithmetic mean? Think about the 
mathematical formula for a mean. How would you translate that into C code? 
And where would you store the result?

Exactly! It goes right inside main() .

So, the complete "Hello, World!" program would look like this:

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

printf("Hello, World!");
   return 0;
}

You've successfully put together your very first C program structure! How 
does that feel? Do you want to try compiling and running this "Hello, World!" 
program to see it in action, or should we move on to using scanf()  to get 
input from the user? 😊

No worries at all! It's completely normal to feel a bit unsure when you're just 
starting out. Let's break it down.

We want to store two numbers, right? And we know they'll be whole numbers, 
which means we'll use the int  type.

If you wanted to store one number and called its variable firstNumber , how 
would you declare that?

C

int firstNumber;

int  variable, giving it a different name. Maybe secondNumber ?

So, putting it together, how do you think you'd declare two integer variables, 
say, num1  and num2 , in your main  function?

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

// How would you declare your two integer variables here?

return 0;
}

You're incredibly close! You've got the scanf  calls correct for reading two 
separate numbers.

Now, remember how important it is to guide the user? If you just have

scanf("%d", &num1);  by itself, the user sees a blank screen and has no 
idea what to type. That's where our friend printf()  comes in again to add 
helpful messages.

scanf()  to tell the user what to do?

Think about what messages you'd want to display to the user. Something like 
"Enter the first number: " and "Enter the second number: ".

Give it a try in the full main  function structure we've been building:

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int num1, num2;

// Your code to prompt and read the first number here

// Your code to prompt and read the second number here

return 0;
}

That's a good start for a prompt! It tells the user what to do.

However, remember we're reading two separate numbers into two separate 
variables ( num1  and num2 ). While printf("Type two numbers");  is okay, it 
might be clearer to prompt for each number individually. This makes it very 
obvious to the user when to type the first number and when to type the 
second.

Think of it like this:

"Please enter the first number:"
(user types 5)
"Please enter the second number:"
(user types 10)

This way, the user knows exactly what input is expected at each step.

You've already got the int num1, num2;  declaration. Now let's fill in the rest 
of main() :

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int num1, num2;

// Prompt for the first number and read it

// Prompt for the second number and read it

return 0;
}

What would you write in place of those comments?

Fantastic! You've absolutely nailed it.

This code snippet is perfect for prompting the user and reading their two 
numbers into num1  and num2 . You've successfully managed the input part 
of our problem!

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int num1, num2;

printf("Please enter the first number: "); // Prompt for the first number
  scanf("%d", &num1);                       // Read into num1

printf("Please enter the second number: "); // Prompt for the second numb
  scanf("%d", &num2);                       // Read into num2

// Next, we'll compare these numbers!

return 0;
}




Comparing Numbers with if  and else

Now that we have the two numbers, num1  and num2 , stored in our program, 
the next big step is to compare them to find out which one is larger. This is 
where conditional statements come in handy.

In C, the most common way to make decisions in your code is by using the

if  and else  keywords. They allow your program to execute different 
blocks of code based on whether a certain condition is true or false.

Here's the basic idea:

C

if (condition is true) {

// Do this code
} else {

// Do this code instead (if the condition was false)
}

Let's look at a simple example:

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int score = 75;

if (score >= 60) { // Is score greater than or equal to 60?
     printf("You passed!\n");
  } else {
     printf("You need to study more.\n");
  }

return 0;
}

In this example, since score  (75) is indeed greater than or equal to 60, the 
program prints "You passed!". If score  were, say, 45, it would print "You 
need to study more."

Now, thinking about our problem: we want to compare num1  and num2  to 
see which is the largest.

What condition would you write inside an if  statement to check if num1  is 
greater than num2 ? And if that condition is true, what would you want your 
program to printf() ?

Think about how you'd structure the if  statement using num1  and num2 . 
You don't need to worry about the else  part just yet; let's focus on the first 
comparison.

if(number % 2 == 0){
printf("even");
}else if(number % 2 == 1){
printf("odd");

You are absolutely, brilliantly, 100% on the right track with number % 2 ! 
That's exactly the operator we need!

Let's look at your code structure:

C

if(number % 2 == 0){

printf("even");
} else if(number % 2 == 1){

printf("odd");
} else {

printf("zero"); // <-- What is this part for?
}

You've correctly used number % 2 == 0  for even numbers. Fantastic!

Now, think about what number % 2  can possibly be when you divide an 
integer by 2. We just talked about it! What are the only two remainders you 
can get?

Given those two possibilities, what does that mean for your else if  and the 
final else  statement? Do we always need all three parts? What would cause 
the else  (the printf("zero")  part) to ever be executed?

Exactly! If number % 2  is not 0, then it must be 1.

Knowing this, let's revisit your code structure:

C

if(number % 2 == 0){

printf("even");
} else if(number % 2 == 1){ // If it's not 0, it HAS to be 1!

printf("odd");
} else { // Will this part ever be reached if it's always 0 or 1?

printf("zero");
}

Do you still think that final else { printf("zero"); }  block is necessary? 
What could you do instead of else if(number % 2 == 1) ? Think about what

else  means in an if-else  structure.

scanf("%d", &n1);
scanf("%d", &n2);
scanf("%d", &n3);

int n1, n2, n3
printf("Type 3 numbers)
scanf("%d", &n1);
scanf("%d", &n2);
scanf("%d", &n3);

You're so close! You have all the core pieces for the input part.

Let's make sure it's a complete, runnable C program. Every C program needs 
a few standard things:

1. 
A header file for input/output functions (like printf  and scanf ). This 
is usually stdio.h . You include it with #include <stdio.h> .

2. 
A main  function, which is where your program execution begins. It 
looks like int main() { ... return 0; } .

Take your lines and put them into this full program structure. Give it a shot!

C

// What goes here to include the standard input/output library?

// This is where your program starts executing
int main() {

// Your variable declaration goes here:
   // int n1, n2, n3;

// Your prompt for the user:
   // printf("Type 3 numbers");

// Your scanf statements:
   // scanf("%d", &n1);
   // scanf("%d", &n2);
   // scanf("%d", &n3);

// This tells the operating system the program finished successfully
   return 0;
}

You're doing great with this step-by-step process!

You got it! Let's explore how to handle collections of data efficiently.

Imagine you have a list of 10 different scores from a test. You could create 
individual variables:

C

int score1;
int score2;

int score3;
// ... all the way to score10;

And then read them one by one:

C

scanf("%d", &score1);
scanf("%d", &score2);
// ... and so on

That works, but it's a lot of typing, and it gets really unwieldy if you suddenly 
need to handle 100 scores, or 1000! There has to be a better way, right?

This is where arrays come in handy!

An array is like a list of variables of the same type, all stored together under a 
single name. You can think of it as a row of connected boxes, each capable 
of holding the same type of item.

Here's how you declare an array of integers that can hold 10 numbers:

C

int numbers[10]; // This declares an array named 'numbers' that can hold 10




To access a specific box (or "element") in the array, you use its index, which 
is its position in the list. Importantly, in C, array indices start from 0.

So, for an array of 10 elements:

The first element is at numbers[0]

The second element is at numbers[1]

...

The tenth (and last) element is at numbers[9]

Here's a small example of using an array:

C

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int ages[3]; // An array to hold 3 ages

ages[0] = 25; // Store 25 in the first position
   ages[1] = 30; // Store 30 in the second position
   ages[2] = 22; // Store 22 in the third position

printf("The first age is: %d\n", ages[0]);
   printf("The second age is: %d\n", ages[1]);
   printf("The third age is: %d\n", ages[2]);

return 0;
}

Looking at this example, how would you declare an array to store the 10 
integer numbers required by your exercise? And how would you access, say, 
the fifth number in that array?

