Ah, scanf ! You're absolutely right, scanf  is super important for getting 
input from the user into your program. Great job remembering that!

However, my previous question was specifically about how to pass a variable 
from one part of your program to a function so the function can use that 
variable. Think about it this way:

If your main  function gets the number using scanf , how do you then tell 
your sayHello  (or in your case, your printMonth ) function what that 
number is so the function can work with it?

scanf  is for getting the data initially. Now, how do we hand that data over to 
our function?

Let's stick with our sayHello  example for a moment. If main  asks the user 
for their age  (using scanf ), and then we want sayHello  to print that 
specific age , what would sayHello  look like in its definition? And how would 
we call it from main ?

C

#include <stdio.h>

// How would we define sayHello here to accept an age?
// void sayHello(...) {
//     printf("Your age is: %d\n", ...);
// }

int main() {

int userAge;
   printf("Please enter your age: ");
   scanf("%d", &userAge);

// How would we call sayHello here to pass userAge to it?
   // sayHello(...);

return 0;
}

What goes in those parentheses (...)  in both the function definition and 
the function call?

Yes, you got it! We'll be working with a "number." But in C, when you declare 
a variable or a function parameter, you always need to tell the compiler what 
type of data it is. Is it a whole number ( int ), a decimal number ( float  or

double ), a single character ( char ), etc.?

For your exercise, you mentioned an "integer number," so what type would 
that be in C?

Once you know the type, think about how you'd write it within the 
parentheses of the function definition:

C

#include <stdio.h>

// How would we define sayHello to accept an integer age?
// We need to specify the type AND a name for the parameter inside the funct
void sayHello( /* type name_of_parameter */ ) {

printf("Your age is: %d\n", /* use the name_of_parameter here */ );
}

int main() {

int userAge;
   printf("Please enter your age: ");
   scanf("%d", &userAge);

// And how would we call sayHello, passing the actual 'userAge' variable
   sayHello( /* variable_to_pass */ );

return 0;
}

What goes in place of /* type name_of_parameter */  and /*

variable_to_pass */ ? Give it a shot! 😊

